properties.title: Fern Room Ceiling
properties.description: Andy Marfia posted a photo: The Fern Room at the Garfield Park Conservatory. The Conservatory was hit last week by golf ball sized hail, which left this room, as well as several others, severely damaged. I stopped by yesterday to take these photos. The Conservatory is open to the public, but currently only 3 of the 8 display houses are accessible. The 103 year old building is truley one of the unsung gems of Chicago, and it's heartbreaking to see it in such condition. I took this and the next two photos from the adjacent Palm House. City workers were actively working to put up barriers to seal off the fern room, but they allowed me to peer inside to take these photos. ¬© Andy Marfia 2011

properties.title: Endangered Species: Rooftop TV Antenna
properties.description: johnfromtheradio posted a photo: Look up to the rooftops in your neighborhood, chances are these are becoming a rare sight. There was a time that you NEEDED something like this, or perhaps one much larger if you are in a "fringe" area, far from the transmitters, out in the boonies (the place to be!) if you were to see any TV programming. Now that most TV is delivered to the home via coaxial cable, fiber optic, or satellite, these are being dismantled and tossed out, sadly. Most people find out the hard way that, when the cable is out, or the satellite doesn't work, their old rooftop antenna would still faithfully squeeze the millivolts of TV signals still available out there, floating in the air. This is a fairly typical antenna for suburban Chicago. The longer elements on the right side are arranged in what's called a "log-periodic" array (longer to shorter) and are used for the old VHF channels 2-13. The smallest elements on the left are called the UHF "corner reflector" and are for channels 14-83 (this part will work extremely well for today's "digital" HDTV reception). This one is pointed right at downtown Chicago, roughly 8 o'clock in this picture (northeast in real life). More info than you ever needed I'm sure.

properties.title: Creating a tabletop sunset
properties.description: Rigib posted a photo: This was a challenge indeed ... creating a "golden hour" setting. I wanted long shadows, a fuzzy horizon, a sun, orange sky. I knew the light had to be from the back from a previous challenge on backlighting so there are three lamps all pointing toward the orange paper away from Farmer Smurf. I tried using a bit of yellow paper, but it didn't work out so I ended up with just two sheets of orange, which are more orangey than this photo shows. The sun was created with a small flashlight. handheld just above Farmer Smurf's head but pointing at the same spot you see here. I used the Canon 60mm close-up lens (my favorite of all lens) set on f/2.8. I set the white balance to "cloudy" which gave it more orangeyness. I focused on Farmer Smurf's tail. Voila!

properties.title: Sanctuary. A scene from Transformers 3 was filmed right here in this room. Abandoned City Methodist Church in Gary, Indiana. HDR
properties.description: slworking2 posted a photo: The city of Gary, Indiana was founded as a booming steel city as the twentieth century passed, and areas downtown saw the construction of several impressive buildings during these prosperous early years. In 1925, a cornerstone ceremony took place at 577 Washington St. to commemorate the construction of a Gothic Revival church called City Methodist. It was completed 21 months later, at the cost of one million dollars - $385,000 of which was contributed by the United States Steel Corp. (which also founded the city). Elbert Gary, the chairman of U.S. Steel and origin of the city's name, donated a Skinner organ as well. The Bedford limestone structure consisted of a 50-foot tall sanctuary nave and elaborate stonework, and was able to seat 950 worshipers; City Methodist had a congregation of nearly 3,000 members in its heyday. The building was also home to Seaman Hall - a 1,000 seat auditorium, and a gymnasium with a full size basketball court. Storefronts were built into the building, with hopes that the income would offset the enormous maintenance costs. During the 1920s, Pastor William Seaman rallied against the power of the Ku Klux Klan in Indiana, and welcomed black worshipers into City Methodist during a time when African Americans were not permitted in "white churches." Gary entered a downward spiral during the 1960s, like many other industrial cities during the period. As U.S. Steel employment dwindled, the residents of Gary moved to nearby suburbs; then as jobs left downtown, city many residents moved out altogether while crime and poverty rose. By 1973 the church's congregation had only 300 members and by 1975 the Methodists moved out of the structure. A second congregation occupied the building until they left in the early 1980s; some storefronts and office space was utilized for a while but soon the entire campus was completely abandoned. City Methodist was burned in the Great Gary Arson of 1997, resulting in a large portion of the roof collapsed or missing. It is now owned by the city of Gary, and its future remains unclear.

properties.description: Rigib posted a photo: Fancy Nancy is a popular storybook character, created by Jane O'Connor. She likes everything fancy so fills her life with frills and lace and glamour. JoJo is Fancy Nancy's sister. For many, many books she wasn't even given a name. I love her bright face and happy smile. She stands next to the kitchen sink by my radio ... the only doll in the kitchen. She sees most of my photo taking, my cooking and dish washing, my eating, my Sudoku puzzling, my bill paying, my cat feeding, my tax preparing ... a great deal of my life. If I could only keep one doll, it would be JoJo.Portrait - Our Daily Challenge 98# of 365

They were not only showing, but working at the horse show. They run a family video business at the shows called Star Creek Video and what I capture in stills, they capture in video. Truth be told, they asked me to take this shot of the two of them and I was happy to oblige. They're pulling just as many hours, if not more, than I am and they always have a smile on their faces! Looking forward to another long but fun day tomorrow!

properties.title: Marina City, Home of Murray "The Camel" Humphreys
properties.description: Chicago Crime Scenes posted a photo: Murray "The Camel" Humphreys was a career mobster who took over as the political manipulator for the Chicago Outfit during the 50s and 60s. He used his connections in the city and federal government to influence lawmakers in the interests of the mob. On November 23, 1965 Humphreys was indicted by a grand jury for perjury. The FBI came to Humphreys condo on the 51st floor of the east tower of Marina City (on the right in the photo) to arrest him. After a brief armed and physical confrontation, Humphreys was taken taken into custody and released on bond later that day. After returning to his Marina City home, he had a heart attack and died. He was 65. Located at 300 N. State St.

properties.title: The Belmont, Home of Angelo "Bloody Angelo" Genna
properties.description: Chicago Crime Scenes posted a photo: Angelo Genna, aka "Bloody Angelo," was one of the six famous Genna brothers. Members of the Chicago's Sicilian Mafia, they specialized in bootlegging industrial or corn syrup alcohol. The Gennas' transgressions into the Irish North Side gang's territory led to conflicts with Dean O'Banion, South Side gang leader Johnny Torrio and Unione Siciliane boss Mike Merlo. Angelo is believed to have been murdered by George "Bugs" Moran and Vincent "Scehemer" Drucci after a high-speed car chase on May 27, 1925. Located at 3170 N. Sheridan Road.
